		@H Historical Background @L
		In Lugdunum, we discussed humanitarian impacts of the Gallic Wars from the native perspective; this time we will focus on the Roman point of view. @L@L
		By now, you should understand the underlying reasons for seeking conquest; but one neglected topic is that Gauls were often conducting raids on Roman trade outposts and caravans. During an occupation, Gallic armies would also often massacre any Romans that could be captured including civilians and merchants. @L@L
		In a way, these actions were even more targeted since the Romans often fought to prevent Germans from crossing the Rhine and would fiercely oppose any enemy who wished to intrude on their land or the land of their client states or allies. One cannot say that they dealt with one ethnic or cultural group harsher just for these reasons. Usually, for example, a massacre of traders would trigger a brutal response in return, and depending on how the reaction to an occupation unfolded, measures would be taken accordingly. @L@L
		One notable example of brutality was after the siege of Alesia, where the city of Uxellodunum, being the last in Gaul that resisted Roman occupation, was subjected to extreme brutality by Julius Caesar. After the siege, all captives were blinded, had their hands and ears cut off, and then released into the countryside. One could consider this a pure terror tactic used to control the remaining populace of Gaul. @L@L
		On the other hand, it might have been this very harsh treatment which prevented Gaul from rising in revolt even though Rome itself was heavily embroiled in civil wars very soon after Gaul's subjugation. @L@L@L@L

 
